ador to UNESCO\n*[[Aziz Vrioni]] \u2013  Ottoman-Albanian politician\n*[[Dhimit\u00ebr Tutulani]] \u2013  Albanian lawyer and politician\n*[[Kas\u00ebm Trebeshina]] \u2013  Albanian partisan, communist prosecutor, actor, and writer\n*[[Sotir Kolea]] \u2013  Albanian folklorist, diplomat and activist of the Albanian National Awakening\n\n===Military===\n*[[Omer Vrioni]] \u2013  Leading Ottoman figure in the Greek War of Independence\n*[[Margarita Tutulani]] \u2013  Anti-fascist and hero of Albania during World War II\n\n===Physicists===\n*[[Af\u00ebrdita Veve\u00e7ka Priftaj]] \u2013  Albanian physicist\n\n===Cinema===\n*[[Kozma Dushi]] \u2013  Albanian recording artist\n\n===Musicians===\n*[[Eni Koci]] \u2013  Albanian female singer\n\n===Religious===\n*[[Christopher of Albania]] \u2013  Primate of the Orthodox Autocephalous Church of Albania from 1937 to 1948\n\n===Sport===\n*[[Myrto Uzuni]] \u2013  Albanian professional footballer who plays as a winger for Croatian club Lokomotiva and the Albania national team\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Codex Beratinus]]\n* [[List of mayors of Berat]]\n* [[Onufri]]\n* [[Osum Canyon]]\n* [[Tomorr Mountain]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Diodorus Siculus]], ''Bibliotheca'' chapters xviii, xix, xx\n* [[Plutarch]], ''[[Parallel Lives]]'', \"[[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius]]\", 18, 31; \"[[Phocion]]\", 31\n* Franca Landucci Gattinoni: L'arte del potere. Vita e opere di Cassandro di Macedonia. Stuttgart 2003. {{ISBN|3-515-08381-2}}\n* ''The Cambridge ancient history'', page 92\n* ''The Regional Directorate of National Culture''\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Berat}}\n{{wikivoyage|Berat}}\n*[http://www.bashkiaberat.gov.al Municipality of Berat]\n*[http://www.muzeumet-berat.al/ Berat Museums]\n*[http://www.goberat.com/ Tourism Information on Berat]\n*[http://gigapan.org/viewGigapan.php?id=32429 1720 megapixel photo of the citdel of Berat]\n*[http://www.journey-stories.com/berat/ Photos of Berat, 2015 year]\n*{{cite news|last1=Byrne|first1=Jane|title=Just Back: Candied walnuts and communism in Albania|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/albania/11782991/Just-Back-Candied-walnuts-and-communism-in-Albania.html|publisher=Telegraph|date=4 Aug 2015}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Berat County}}\n{{Berat Municipality}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in Albania}}\n{{Cultural Monuments in Berat County}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Berat| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Albania]]\n[[Category:Ottoman architecture in Albania| ]]\n[[Category:Antipatrid colonies]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek archaeological sites in Albania]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Municipalities in Berat County]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Berat]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the locality in Queensland, Australia|Berat, Queensland}}\n{{for|the Ottoman licence|Beratl\u0131}}<!--Source: https://menadoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/menalib/download/pdf/2734659?originalFilename=true - page 30, pdf p. 32-->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement (Albanian)\n| type = m\n| nickname = City of one above other windows\n| flag =\n| emblem = [[File:Stema e Bashkis\u00eb Berat.svg|70px]]\n| skyline = {{Photomontage|position=center\n| photo1a = Berat_Unesco_2016_Albania.jpg\n| photo2a = Old_town_of_berat_1.jpg\n| photo2b = Old_town_of_berat_2_albania_2016.jpg\n| photo3a = BERAT_Unesco_Albania_2016.jpg\n| photo3b = The old city of Berat.jpg\n| photo4a = Panorama_of_Berat,_Albania_2016.jpg\n   | size = 280\n   | spacing = 2\n   | color = #FFFFFFu\n   | border = 0\n   | foot_montage = {{nobreak|Berat}} photomontage}} \n| caption = \n| county = [[File:Stema e Qarkut Berat.svg|15px]] [[Berat County|Berat]]\n| mayor = Ervin Demo\n| party = [[Socialist Party of Albania|PS]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|N|19|57|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline}}\n| elevation = 58\n| area munic = 380.21\n| area unit = \n| population as of = 2011\n| population munic = 65453\n| population unit = 37606\n| demonym = Beratas ''(m)''<br> Beratase ''(f)''\n| postal code = 5001-5006\n| area code = (0)311\n| vehicle plate = BR\n| website = {{URL|http://bashkiaberat.gov.al|Official Website}}\n{{designation list |embed = yes\n|designation1 = WHS\n|designation1_offname = [[Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastra]]\n|designation1_date = 2005\n|designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/569 569]\n|designation1_criteria = iii, iv\n|designation1_type = Cultural\n|designation1_free1name = Region\n|designation1_free1value = [[Berat County]]\n|designation1_free2name = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe|Europe]]\n|designation1_free2value = 2005\u2013present\n}}|name=}}\n\n'''Berat''' ({{IPA-sq|\u02c8b\u025b:rat}}, {{lang-sq-definite|Berati}}), is the [[List of cities in Albania|ninth largest city]] by population of the [[Republic of Albania]]. The city is the capital of the surrounding [[Berat County]], one of 12 constituent [[Counties of Albania|counties]] of the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |title=Law nr. 115/2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=2 June 2015 }}</ref> By air, it is {{convert|71|km|abbr=off}} north of [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]], {{convert|70|km|abbr=off}} west of [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], {{convert|70|km|abbr=off}} south of [[Tirana]] and {{convert|33|km|abbr=off}} east of [[Fier]].\n\nBerat is located in the south of the country, 120 km south of Tirana. It is surrounded by mountains and hills including [[Tomorr]] on the east that was declared a [[Tomorr National Park|national park]]. The river [[Osum (river)|Osum]] (total length {{convert|161|km|abbr=on}}) runs through the city before it empties into the [[Seman (river)|Seman]] within the [[Myzeqe|Myzeqe Plain]]. The municipality of Berat was formed at the 2015 local government reform by the merger of the former municipalities Berat, [[Otllak]], [[Roshnik]], [[Sinj\u00eb]] and [[Velabisht]], that became municipal units. The seat of the municipality is the city Berat.<ref>[http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf Law nr. 115/2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The total population is 60,031 (2011 census),<ref name=\"census11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/3059/1__berat.pdf |title=Population and housing census - Berat 2011 |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Institute of Statistics (Albania)|INSTAT]] }}</ref> in a total area of {{cvt|380.21|km2}}.<ref name=\"LAU\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/345175/501971/EU-28-LAU-2019-NUTS-2016.xlsx |title=Correspondence table LAU \u2013 NUTS 2016, EU-28 and EFTA / available Candidate Countries |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Eurostat]]|format=XLS }}</ref> The population of the former municipality at the 2011 census was 32,606.<ref name=census11/>\n\nBerat, designated a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] in 2008, comprises a unique style of [[Architecture of Albania|architecture]] with influences from several civilizations that have managed to coexist for centuries throughout the [[History of Albania|history]]. Like many cities in Albania, Berat comprises an old fortified city filled with churches and mosques painted with grandiose wealth of visible [[mural]]s and [[fresco]]s. Berat is one of the main cultural centres of the country.<ref name=\"Norris56\"/>\n\n==Name==\n\nThe name of the city in Albanian is \"Berat\" or \"Berati\", which is probably derived from the [[Old Slavonic language|Old Slavonic]] \u0411\u0463\u043b\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u044a or \"''Bel(i)grad''\"{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} (\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434, meaning \"white city\" in the [[South Slavic languages]]), under which name it was known in Greek, Bulgarian, Latin and Slavic documents during the High and Late Middle Ages.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} That name was rendered as ''Bellegrada'' (\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03b4\u03b1) in Greek.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} It is believed to have been the site of the ancient city \"''Antipatreia''\" ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}} \"city of [[Antipater]]\") or \"''Antipatrea''\" in [[Latin language|Latin]], while during the early [[Byzantine Empire]] the name of the town was \"Pulcheriopolis\" ({{lang-el|\u03a0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03c7\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2}}, \"city of [[Pulcheria]]\").<ref name=\"FishtaElsie2005\"/><ref name=\"HammondWalbank1988\">{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=N.G.L. |last2=Walbank |first2=F.W. |title=A History of Macedonia: Volume III: 336-167 B.C. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qpb3JdwuDQIC&pg=PA391 |accessdate=9 January 2011 |year=1988 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-814815-9 |page=391}}</ref> In the [[Republic of Venice]] the city was known as ''Belgrado di Romania'' ([[Rumelia#Etymology|Rumelian]] Belgrade), while in the [[Ottoman Empire]] it was also known as ''Belgrad-i Arnavud'' (Albanian Belgrade) to distinguish it from [[Belgrade]].<ref name=\"FishtaElsie2005\">{{cite book |last1=Fishta |first1=Gjergj |others=Elsie, Robert; Mathie-Heck, Janice (trans.) |publisher=Centre for Albanian Studies |location=London |title=The highland lute: (Lahuta e Malc\u00eds) : the Albanian national epic |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=j7tLgANw8hAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=highland+lute&hl=en&src=bmrr&ei=JyAqTc-cDYis8gPytq3PAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false |accessdate=9 January 2011 |year=2005 |agency=I.B.Tauris |isbn=978-1-84511-118-2 |page=405}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:2011 Berat, Most Gorica 02.JPG|thumb|left|Berat, Albania.]]\nBerat lies on the right bank of the river [[Osum (Albania)|Osum]], a short distance from the point where it is joined by the [[Molisht]] river. The old city centre consists of three parts: Kalaja (on the castle hill), Mangalem (at the foot of the castle hill) and Gorica (on the left bank of the Osum). It has a wealth of beautiful buildings of high architectural and historical interest. The pine forests above the city, on the slopes of the towering [[Tomorr]] mountains, provide a backdrop of appropriate grandeur. The Osumi river has cut a 915-metre deep gorge through the limestone rock on the west side of the valley to form a precipitous natural fortress, around which the town was built on several river terraces.\n\nAccording to an Albanian legend, the Tomorr mountain was originally a giant, who fought with another giant (mountain) called Shpirag over a young woman. They killed each other and the girl drowned in her tears, which then became the Osum river.\n\n[[Mount Shpirag]], named after the second giant, is on the left bank of the gorge, above the district of Gorica. Berat is known to Albanians as the city of \"One above another Windows\" (a similar epithet is sometimes applied to [[Gjirokastra]]), or ''The City of Two Thousand Steps''. It was proclaimed a 'Museum City' by the dictator [[Enver Hoxha]] in June 1961.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Ancient ===\nThe earliest recorded inhabitants of the city (6th century BC) were the ancient Greek tribe of the [[Dassaretae]] or Dexarioi, the northernmost subgroup of the [[Chaonians]], and the region was known as ''Dessaretis'' after them.<ref name=\"HammondWalbank1988\" /><ref name=\"LewisBoardman1994\">{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=D. M.|last2=Boardman|first2=John|title=The Cambridge ancient history: The fourth century B.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vx251bK988gC&pg=PA423|accessdate=11 January 2011|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-23348-4|page=423}}</ref> Modern Berat occupies the site of ''Antipatreia'' ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}), which originally was a settlement of the Dexarioi<ref name=\"Wilkes\">{{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=John J.|title=The Illyrians|location=Oxford|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|year=1995|isbn=0-631-19807-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Nv6SPRKqs8C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false}}</ref> and later a [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonian]] stronghold in southern [[Illyria]].<ref name=\"HammondWalbank1988\" /><ref name=\"CohenWalbank1995\">{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Getzel M.|last2=Walbank|first2=F. W.|title=The Hellenistic settlements in Europe, the islands, and Asia Minor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnsPcZW4G7YC&pg=PA76|accessdate=9 January 2011|year=1995|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-08329-5|page=76}}</ref> The founding date is unknown, although if [[Cassander]] is the founder it has been suggested that Antipatreia was founded after he took control of the region around 314 BC.<ref name=\"CohenWalbank1995\"/> In 200 BC it was captured by the [[Roman Republic|Roman]] [[legatus]] Lucius Apustius, who razed the walls and massacred the male population of the city.<ref name=\"Astin1998\">{{cite book|last=Astin|first=A. E.|title=The Cambridge ancient history: Rome and the Mediterranean to 133 B.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Oe1u1H_OSMC&pg=PA262|accessdate=11 January 2011|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-23448-1|page=262}}</ref><ref name=\"Walbank1967\">{{cite book|last=Walbank|first=Frank William|title=Philip V of Macedon|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=BZAsTem-NtS84gbuh6WOCw&ct=result&hl=el&id=qkobAAAAYAAJ&dq=antipatreia+%2B+massacre&q=male+population#search_anchor|accessdate=11 January 2011|year=1967|publisher=Archon Books|page=138}}</ref>\n\n=== Medieval ===\nThe town became part of the unstable frontier of the [[Byzantine Empire]] following the fall of the [[western Roman Empire]] and, along with much of the rest of the [[Balkan peninsula]], it suffered from repeated invasions by [[Slavic people|Slavs]]. During the Roman and early Byzantine period, the city was known as ''Pulcheriopolis''.\n\nThe [[First Bulgarian Empire]] under [[Presian I of Bulgaria|Presian I]] captured the town in the 9th century, and the city received the Slavic name ''Bel[i]grad'' (\"White City\"), Belegrada (\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03b4\u03b1) in Greek, which persisted throughout the medieval period, changing to ''Berat'' under Ottoman rule. The town became one of the most important towns in the Bulgarian region [[Kutmichevitsa]]. The Bulgarian governor [[Elemag]] surrendered the city to the emperor [[Basil II]] in 1018, and the city remained in Byzantine hands until the [[Second Bulgarian Empire]] retook the city in 1203 during the rule of [[Kaloyan of Bulgaria|Kaloyan]]. During the 13th century, it fell to [[Michael I Ducas]], the ruler of the [[Despotate of Epirus]].\n\n[[File:Berat Albania 15.jpg|thumb|left|230px|The entrance of the citadel, with the 13th century Byzantine [[Holy Trinity Church, Berat|Holy Trinity Church]].]]\n\nByzantine Emperor [[Michael VIII Palaiologos]] sent letters to the Albanian leaders of Berat and [[Durr\u00ebs]] in 1272 asking them to abandon their alliance with [[Charles I of Naples]], leader of the [[Kingdom of Albania (medieval)|Kingdom of Albania]], who had captured and incorporated it at the same period in the Kingdom of Albania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etd.ceu.hu/2009/mphlae01.pdf|title=Regnum Albaniae and the Papal Curia|last=Lala|first=Etleva|author2=Gerhard Jaritz|year=2008|publisher=Central European University|page=32|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Wirth1977\">{{cite book|last=Wirth|first=Peter|title=Regesten der Kaiserurkunden des ostr\u00f6mischen Reiches von 565-1453: Regesten von 1204-1282|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=qsM339yaKZMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Regesten+und+Kaiserurkunden&source=bl&ots=aDW22ULQ_V&sig=Uuz54fCUhMkAPAXSPFNpfSegnaI&hl=en&ei=nxlLTbTQF4GDOoXVrfEP&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false|accessdate=3 February 2011|date=2 March 1977|publisher=C.H.Beck|isbn=978-3-406-00738-5|page=114}}</ref><ref name=\"Norris36\">{{cite book|last=Norris|first=Harry Thirlwall|title=Islam in the Balkans: religion and society between Europe and the Arab world|year=1993|location=Columbia|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|url=https://archive.org/details/islaminbalkansre00norr|url-access=registration|isbn=9780872499775|page=[https://archive.org/details/islaminbalkansre00norr/page/36 36]|ref=harv}}</ref> However, they sent the letters to Charles as a sign of their loyalty.<ref name=\"Nicol2010\">{{cite book|last=Nicol|first=Donald M.|title=The Despotate of Epiros 1267-1479: A Contribution to the History of Greece in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=XIj0FfKto9AC&pg=PA109&dq=Tomoritsa&hl=en&ei=-DhHTdCOO4Wq8QOWmYWvCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=In%201272%20he%20wrote%20the%20Albanians%20of%20Durazzo%20and%20Berat%20urging%20them%20to%20renounce&f=false|accessdate=1 February 2011|date=11 February 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-13089-9|page=16}}</ref>\nIn 1274 Michael VIII recaptured Berat and after being joined by Albanians who supported the Byzantine Empire, marched unsuccessfully against the Angevin capital of Durr\u00ebs.<ref name=\"Bartusis1997\">{{cite book|last=Bartusis|first=Mark C.|title=The late Byzantine army: arms and society, 1204-1453|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rUs-hHd89xAC&pg=PA62|accessdate=1 February 2011|year=1997|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-1620-2|page=62}}</ref> In 1280-1281 the Sicilian forces under [[Hugh the Red of Sully]] [[Siege of Berat (1280\u20131281)|laid siege]] to Berat. In March 1281 a relief force from [[Constantinople]] under the command of [[Michael Tarchaneiotes]] was able to drive off the besieging Sicilian army.<ref>Norwich, John Julius. ''The Decline and Fall of the Byzantine Empire''. (New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1996) p. 246-247</ref> Later in the 13th century Berat again fell under the control of the Byzantine Empire. \n\nIn 1335 Albanians from [[Epirus Nova]] invaded the area of Berat and appeared in Epirus for the first time,<ref>Steven G. Ellis, Lud'a Klus\u00e1kov\u00e1. [https://books.google.gr/books?id=3zXFCs9EfEYC&pg=PA125&dq=epirus%2Bmedieval&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=2#v=snippet&q=%22Albanians%20of%20Epirus%20Nova%20invaded%20the%20area%20of%20Berat%20and%20appeared%20for%20the%20first%20time%20in%20Epirus%22&f=false ''Imagining frontiers, contesting identities.''] Edizioni Plus, 2007 {{ISBN|978-88-8492-466-7}}, p. 134 \"In 1337 the Albanians of Epirus Nova invaded the area of Berat and appeared for the first time in Epirus\".</ref><ref>Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re Hammond. [https://books.google.gr/books?id=_VBoAAAAMAAJ&q=%22By+1335+they+were+in+possession+also+of+the+area+between+Berat+and+the+Gulf+of+Valona%22&dq=%22By+1335+they+were+in+possession+also+of+the+area+between+Berat+and+the+Gulf+of+Valona%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=0&cd=1 ''Migrations and invasions in Greece and adjacent areas'']. Noyes Press, 1976, {{ISBN|978-0-8155-5047-1}}, p. 61 \"By 1335 they were in possession also of the area between Berat and the Gulf of Valona\"</ref> while in 1345 (or maybe 1343) the town passed to the [[Serbian Empire]].<ref name=\"Nicol1984\">{{cite book|last=Nicol|first=Donald M.|authorlink=Donald M. Nicol|title=The Despotate of Epiros 1267-1479: A Contribution to the History of Greece in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIj0FfKto9AC&pg=PA128|year=1984|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-26190-6|page=128|quote=Berat may have fallen by 1343.}}</ref> After its dissolution in 1355 Berat came under suzerainty of its former governor, [[John Komnenos Asen]] (1345-1363), Alexander Komnenos Asen (1363-1372) and [[Zeta under the Bal\u0161i\u0107i|Zeta]] of [[Bal\u0161a II]] (1372-1385). In 1385 Berat was captured by the Ottomans, before the [[Battle of Savra]]. According to some sources, the Ottomans probably remained in Berat for some time with intention to use it as foothold to capture Valona.<ref name=\"Gibbons2013\">{{cite book|last=Gibbons|first=Herbert Adam|title=The Foundation of the Ottoman Empire: A History of the Osmanlis Up To the Death of Bayezid I 1300-1403|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LQiAAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA159|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-02982-1|page=159}}</ref> By 1396, the Albanian [[Muzaka family]] took over control of Berat which became the capital of the [[Principality of Berat]].<ref name=\"\u0106ur\u010di\u0107Aimos1997\">{{cite book|last1=\u0106ur\u010di\u0107|first1=Slobodan|last2=Aimos|first2=|last3=Preservation|first3=Society for the Study of the Medieval Architecture in the Balkans and its|title=Secular medieval architecture in the Balkans 1300-1500 and its preservation|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=e4wsTeFCn4ziBufa6NYL&ct=result&id=VfhPAAAAMAAJ&dq=Berat+%2B+Muzaka&q=Muzaka+family#search_anchor|accessdate=11 January 2011|year=1997|publisher=Aimos, Society for the Study of the Medieval Architecture in the Balkans and its Preservation|isbn=978-960-86059-1-6|page=114}}</ref><ref name=\"FineFine1994\">{{cite book|last1=Fine|first1=John V. A.|authorlink1=John V. A. Fine|last2=Fine|first2=John Van Antwerp|authorlink2=John Van Antwerp Fine|title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvVbRrH1QBgC&pg=PA391|year=1994|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=0-472-08260-4|page=391|quote=...in 1396. By this time the family of Musachi had gained control of Berat. }}</ref> In 1417 Berat became a part of the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"Kiel48\">{{harvnb|Kiel|1990|p=48}}. \"In 1417, Berat became part of the Ottoman Empire when this strong city succumbed to a surprise attack.\"</ref> In 1455 [[Skanderbeg]], a commander with an Albanian force of 14,000 and small number of Catalan soldiers unsuccessfully tried to [[siege of Berat (1455)|capture Berat]] from an Ottoman force of 40,000.<ref name=\"Setton192\">{{cite book|last=Setton|first=Kenneth Meyer|title=The Papacy and the Levant (1204\u20131571), Volume II. The Fifteenth Century|year=1976|publisher=[[American Philosophical Society]]|isbn=9780871691279|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0Sz2VYI0l1IC&pg=PA192&dq=Skenderbeg+Berat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2m-WF4v7lAhU263MBHRJyDOYQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=Skenderbeg%20Berat&f=false|pages=192|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n=== Modern ===\n\n[[File:Halveti Teqe Berat.jpg|thumb|230px|right|Halveti Tekke]]\n\nDuring the early period of Ottoman rule, Berat fell into severe decline. By the end of the 16th century it had only 710 houses. However, it began to recover by the 17th century and became a major craft centre specializing in wood carving.\n\nDuring the first part of the sixteenth century, Berat was a Christian city and did not contain any Muslim households.<ref name=\"Ergo3437\">{{harvnb|Ergo|2010|pp=34, 37}}.</ref> The urban population of this period (1506-1583) increased little with the addition of 17 houses.<ref name=\"Ergo36\"/> [[Expulsion of Jews from Spain|Following their expulsion and arrival from Spain]],<ref name=\"Mema\"/> a [[Jews in Albania|Jewish community]] existed in Berat that consisted of 25 families between 1519-1520.<ref name=\"Giakoumis96\"/>\n\nToward the latter part of the sixteenth century, Berat contained 461 Muslim houses and another 187 belonged to newcomers from the surrounding villages of Gjeqar, Gjerb\u00ebs, Tozhar, Fratar and Dobronik.<ref name=\"Ergo36\"/> [[Islamization of Albania#Central Albania|Conversion to Islam of the local urban population]] in Berat had increased during this time and part of the newcomer population were also Muslim converts who had Islamic names and Christian surnames.<ref name=\"Ergo36\">{{harvnb|Ergo|2010|p=36}}.</ref> Factors such as tax exemptions for Muslim urban craftsmen in exchange for military service drove many of the incoming rural first generation Muslim population to Berat.<ref name=\"Ergo33\">{{harvnb|Ergo|2010|p=33}}.</ref> Followers of [[Sabbatai Zevi]] existed in Berat among Jews during the mid sixteenth century.<ref name=\"Giakoumis96\"/> The Berat Jewish community took an active role in the welfare of other Jews such as managing to attain the release of war related captives present in Durr\u00ebs in 1596.<ref name=\"Giakoumis96\"/> \n\nFrom 1670 onward, Berat became a Muslim majority city and of its 30 neighbourhoods, 19 were populated by Muslims.<ref name=\"Skendi12\"/> Factors attributed to the change of the urban religious composition in Berat was pressure to covert in some neighbourhoods and a lack of Christian priests being able to provide religious services.<ref name=\"Skendi12\">{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=The Albanian national awakening|year=1967a|location=Princeton|publisher=Princeton University Press|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=8QPWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PR15&dq=The+Albanian+National+Awakening&redir_esc=y&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false|isbn=9781400847761|pages=12|ref=harv}}</ref> By the early seventeenth century, urban life in Berat started to resemble Ottoman and Muslim patterns.<ref name=\"Ergo34\">{{cite book|last=Ergo|first=Dritan|chapter=Islam in the Albanian lands (XVth-XVIIth Century)|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Religion+und+Kultur+im+albanischsprachigen+S%C3%BCdosteuropa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiPvtK4zf3lAhXHfn0KHQHmAasQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false|pages=34|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Naibi gr.jpg|thumb|230px|left|The city of Berat in 1813, illustration by Charles Cockerelle]]\nIn the 18th century, Berat was one of the most important Albanian cities during the [[Ottoman Albania|Ottoman]] period.<ref name=\"AminFortna2006\">{{cite book|last1=Amin|first1=Camron Michael|last2=Fortna|first2=Benjamin C.|last3=Frierson|first3=Elizabeth Brown|title=The modern Middle East: a sourcebook for history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzJkKk6z-zIC&pg=PA569|accessdate=13 January 2011|date=21 April 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-926209-0|page=569}}</ref> In the early modern era the city was the capital of the [[Pashalik of Berat]] founded by [[Ahmet Kurt Pasha]]. Berat was incorporated in the [[Pashalik of Yanina]] after [[Ibrahim Pasha of Berat]] was defeated by [[Ali Pasha of Yanina|Ali Pasha]] in 1809. In 1867, Berat became a [[sanjak]] in [[Yannina]] (Yanya) vilayet. Berat had replaced a declining [[Vlor\u00eb]] as centre of the sanjak (province) in the nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Kiel52\"/> The sanjak of Berat and the city itself were under the dominance of the Albanian [[Vrioni family]].<ref name=\"Kiel52\"/> The [[Romaniote Jews|Jewish community of Yanina]]  renewed the Jewish community of Berat in the nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Giakoumis96\">{{cite book|last=Giakoumis|first=Konstantinos|chapter=The Orthodox Church in Albania Under the Ottoman Rule 15th-19th Century|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Religion+und+Kultur+im+albanischsprachigen+S%C3%BCdosteuropa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiPvtK4zf3lAhXHfn0KHQHmAasQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Berat&f=false|pages=96|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nA Greek school was operating in the city already from 1835.<ref name=katoptron>{{cite web | last=|first=| title=\u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd. [School of Berat] | url=http://195.134.90.78:8080/katoptron/loadUserSchoolInfo.do?schoolId=315 | accessdate=30 October 2010 |work=\u039a\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a6\u03b9\u03bb\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 ([[University of Athens]])|language=Greek}}</ref> In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Orthodox Christians in Berat numbered some 5,000 people of whom 3,000 spoke the [[Aromanian language]] and the rest the [[Albanian language]].<ref name=\"Koukoudis358\">{{cite book|last=Koukoudis|first=Asterios|title=The Vlachs: Metropolis and Diaspora|year=2003|location=Thessaloniki|publisher=Zitros Publications|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=01JoAAAAMAAJ&dq=The+Vlachs%3A+Metropolis+and+Diaspora&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Berat|isbn=9789607760869|pages=358|ref=harv}} \"Berat... At the end of the nineteenth and beginning of the twentieth century, of the 5,000 or so Orthodox Christians in the town, some 3,000 were Vlach-speaking and the rest Albanian-speaking.\"</ref> During the 19th century, Berat played an important part in the [[Albanian national revival]]. Christian merchants in Berat supported the Albanian movement.<ref name=\"Biondich36\">{{Cite book|last=Biondich|first=Mark|title=The Balkans: Revolution, War, and Political Violence Since 1878|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199299058|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=gt8SDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA36&dq=Berat+Albanian+national+revival&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQvuXEvv7lAhWq7nMBHctWBnwQ6AEIOjAC#v=onepage&q=Berat%20Albanian%20national%20revival&f=false|pages=36|ref=harv}}</ref> Berat became a major base of support for the [[League of Prizren]], the late 19th century Albanian nationalist alliance, while the city was also represented in the formation of southern branch of the league in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=Beginnings of Albanian Nationalist and Autonomous Trends: The Albanian League, 1878-1881Author|journal=American Slavic and East European Review|publisher=American Slavic and East European Review|volume=12|page=4|jstor=2491677|quote=The southern branch of the League was formed at Gjinokast\u00ebr (Argyrokastro), where; Albanian leaders held a meeting at which the districts of Janina, Gjinokast\u00ebr, Delvina, P\u00ebrmet, Berat, Vlora (Valona), Filat, Margariti, Ajdonat, Parga, Preveza, Arta, Tepelena, Kolonja, and Korca were represented.}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], Jews were concealed in the homes and basements of 60 families from the Muslim and Christian communities in Berat.<ref name=\"Mema\"/> From 23 to 30 October 1944, the second session of the Council of National Liberation of Albania was held in Berat, where the [[National Liberation Movement (Albania)|National Liberation Movement]]-controlled Anti-Fascist National Liberation Committee became the [[Provisional Democratic Government of Albania]], with [[Enver Hoxha]] as its prime minister and minister of defence.<ref name=\"Pearson2006\">{{cite book |last=Pearson |first=Owen |title=Albania in Occupation and War: From Fascism to Communism 1940-1945 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=P3knunC7z_oC&pg=PA272&dq=Berat+%2B+Balli&hl=en&ei=sUsvTci2OJCB5AbOpKi3Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Berat%20%20Liberation%20committee&f=false |accessdate=13 January 2011 |date=11 July 2006 |agency=I.B.Tauris |isbn=978-1-84511-104-5 |page=399}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\nBy the 18th century the economy and society of Berat was closely connected to the city's craft guilds partly related to various tax exemptions that existed since the late Middle Ages. By 1750 there were twenty-two guilds, the most important of which were the tanners', the cobblers' and other leather-working guilds. Other guilds included metal-working, silver-smithing and silk-making ones.<ref name=\"AminFortna2006\"/>\n\n==Landmarks==\n{{See also|Tourist attractions in Berat}}\n{{wide image|Panorama of Berat, Albania 2016.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|Panorama of Berat}}\n\nThe coexistence of religious and cultural communities over several centuries, beginning in the 4th century BC into the 18th century is apparent in Berat. The town also bears testimony to the architectural excellence of traditional [[Balkans|Balkan]] housing construction, which date to the late 18th and the 19th centuries. Some of the landmarks of that historical period could be seen in the Berat Castle, churches of the Byzantine era such as the Church of St. Mary of Blaherna (13th century), the Bachelors' Mosque, the National Ethnographic Museum, the Sultan's Mosque (built between 1481 and 1512), Leaden Mosque (built in 1555) and the Gorica Bridge.<ref name=Unesco>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/569 |title=UNESCO.orgHistoric Centres of Berat and Gjirokastra|accessdate=2010-09-07|publisher=Unesco.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Castle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.castle-park.com/berat_city.htm|title=The Castle|publisher=Castle Park|accessdate=5 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226023204/http://www.castle-park.com/berat_city.htm|archivedate=26 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BM\"/><ref name=Museum>{{cite web|url=http://albania.shqiperia.com/kat/m/shfaqart/aid/2243/National-Ethnographic-Museum-Berat.html|title=National Ethnographic Museum, Berat|publisher=Albania Shqiperia|accessdate=5 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224085339/http://albania.shqiperia.com/kat/m/shfaqart/aid/2243/National-Ethnographic-Museum-Berat.html|archive-date=24 February 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Berat citadel.jpg|thumb|230px|View of the Citadel of Berat.]]\n\n[[Berat Castle]] is built on a rocky hill on the right bank of the river [[Osum]] and is accessible only from the south. After being burned down by the Romans in 200 BC the walls were strengthened in the 5th century under Byzantine [[Emperor Theodosius II]], and were rebuilt during the 6th century under the Emperor [[Justinian I]] and again in the 13th century under the Despot of Epirus, [[Michael I Komnenos Doukas|Michael Komnenos Doukas]], cousin of the Byzantine Emperor. The main entrance, on the north side, is defended by a fortified courtyard and there are three smaller entrances. The fortress of Berat in its present state, even though considerably damaged, remains a magnificent sight. The surface that it encompasses made it possible to house a considerable portion of the town's inhabitants. The buildings inside the fortress were built during the 13th century and because of their characteristic architecture are preserved as cultural monuments. The population of the fortress was Christian, and it had about 20 churches (most built during the 13th century) and only one mosque, for the use of the Muslim garrison, (of which there survives only a few ruins and the base of the minaret). The churches of the fortress have been damaged through the years and only some remain.\n\nThe [[Church of St. Mary of Blachernae (Berat)|Church of St. Mary of Blachernae]] dating from the 13th century, has 16th century mural paintings by Nikoll\u00eb Onufri, son of the most important post-medieval Albanian painter, [[Onufri]]. In a small tree - planted square, on a hillside inside the walls of the fortress, stands the 14th century Church of the Holy Trinity. It is built in the form of a cross and has Byzantine murals. Outside the ramparts is the Church of St. Michael (Sh\u00ebn Mehill), built in the 13th century. This church is reached by a steep but perfectly safe path. Near the entrance, after a guardhouse, is the little Church of St. Theodore (Shen Todher), which have wall paintings by Onufri himself. The most interesting is the cathedral of St. Nicholas, which has been well restored and is now a museum dedicated to Onufri. Onufri was the greatest of the 16th century painters in Albania. Not only was he a master of the techniques of fresco and icons, but he was the first to introduce a new colour in painting, shiny red, which the French called \"Onufri's Red\". In addition, Onufri introduced a certain realism and a degree of individuality in facial expression.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beratkulture.com/ShenMeriVllaherna.aspx |title=Kisha e Sh\u00ebn M\u00ebri Vllahern\u00ebs |language=Albanian |accessdate=6 November 2010 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n |total_width = 500\n | align = left\n | background color = #BBDD99\n | width = 200\n | image1 =Old town of berat albania 3.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = Old town of berat 1.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | image3 = Old town of berat 2 albania 2016.jpg\n | alt3 = \n | footer_background = #BBDD99\n | footer_align = center\n | footer = The [[UNESCO]] Site of [[Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokast\u00ebr|Berat]].\n}}\n\nThe first inscription recording Onufri's name was found in 1951, in the Shelqan church. The Kastoria church has a date 23 July 1547 and a reference to Onufri's origin : ''I am Onufri, and come from the town of Berat''. Onufri's style in painting was inherited by his son, Nikolla (Nicholas), though not so successful as his father. In Onufri's museum can be found works of Onufri, his son, Nikolla and other painters'. There are also numbers of icons and some fine examples of religious silversmith's work (sacred vessels, icon casings, covers of Gospel books, etc.). Berat Gospels, which date from the 4th century, are copies (the originals are preserved in the National Archives in Tirana). The church itself has a magnificent iconostasis of carved wood, with two very fine icons of Christ and the Virgin Mary. The bishop's throne and the pulpit are also of considerable quality. \nNear the street running down from the fortress is the Bachelors' Mosque (Xhami e Beqareve), built in 1827. This has a handsome portico and an interesting external decoration of flowers, plants, houses, etc. The 'Bachelors' were the young shop-assistants (in practice generally unmarried), whom the merchants in Berat used as their own private militia. \n\nThe [[King Mosque, Berat|King Mosque]] ({{lang-sq|Xhamia e Mbretit}}), the oldest in the town built in the reign of [[Bayazid II]] (1481\u20131512),<ref name=\"Norris56\"/> is notable for its fine ceiling. It is museum in the modern period.<ref name=\"Norris56\">{{harvnb|Norris|1993|p=56}}. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=kTcRDKnYf2cC&pg=PA68&dq=Berat+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi95_SmzP3lAhVZWH0KHduNDsMQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=great%20cultural%20centres&f=false]</ref>\n\nThe [[Lead Mosque, Berat|Lead Mosque]] (Xhamia e Plumbit), built in 1555 and so called from the covering of its cupola. This mosque is the centre of the town.<ref name=\"Mediterranean Europe\">{{cite book|title=Mediterranean Europe|last=Garwood|first=Duncan|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=1-74104-856-7|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbtxTd95IjwC&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Lead+Mosque+berat&source=bl&ots=-pbS2k-0PM&sig=Q447t_98phEWHeHKIMjP6rHkNB0&hl=en&ei=C6hJTLejOJOjONWpnZYD&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CCoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Lead%20Mosque%20berat&f=false|accessdate=23 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Berat_UNESCO_2016_Albania.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Berat as seen from the [[Berat Castle|Castle]].]]\n\nThe [[Halveti Teqe, Berat|Halveti Tekke]] (Teqe e Helvetive) is thought to have been built in the 15th century. It was rebuilt by [[Ahmet Kurt Pasha]] in 1782. It belongs to the [[Khalwati order|Khalwati Sufi order]]. It is composed of the prayer hall with a square plan, a small ambience for special religious services and a gracious portico in front of the entrance to the prayer hall. In the prayer hall is a mafil carved in wood and decorated. On the eastern side of the prayer hall is the [[mihrab]] decorated with stone stalactites. The inner walls have been decorated with eight frescoes, depicting dwelling houses, [[Muslim]] religious buildings and landscapes.\n\nThe walls below the frescoes are covered by holes that improve the acoustics in the prayer hall. The ceiling of the prayer hall is made of wood and is decorated with paintings valued as the most beautiful of the time. The ceiling has been decorated in the [[Baroque style]] adopted in Islamic art and is covered with 14 carat gold plates. The inner decorations were carried out by Master [[Dush Barka]]. Attached to the prayer hall is a room in which once was the mausoleum of [[Ahmet Kurt Pasha]] and his son. The portico of the tekke has five stone columns which were taken from the [[ancient Greek]] city of [[Apollonia, Illyria|Apollonia]]. Above the main door in the portico is an inscription dedicated to the values of the tekke and to [[Ahmet Kurt Pasha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beratkulture.com/THelvetive.aspx|title=Teqja e Helvetive|language=Albanian|accessdate=6 November 2010}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Monuments dating to the late Ottoman period from the Albanian Vrioni family exist such as the gate to a former palace and a tomb, other monuments are from the Vlora family.<ref name=\"Kiel52\">{{cite book|last=Kiel|first=Machiel|title=Ottoman architecture in Albania, 1385-1912|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=2xYzAAAAIAAJ&dq=Berat+ottoman&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Berat+|year=1990|publisher=Research Centre for Islamic History, Art and Culture|isbn=978-92-9063-330-3|page=52|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nNear of tekke is purported to be the grave of [[Sabbatai Zevi]], a [[History of the Jews in the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Jew]] who had been banished to [[Dulcigno]] (present day Ulcinj) who created controversy among his followers upon his conversion to [[Islam]]. A Jewish history museum named \"Solomon Museum\" is located in southern Berat and contains exhibits about the [[Holocaust in Albania]] and the survival of Jews during the war in the country.<ref name=\"Mema\">{{cite news|last=Mema|first=Briseida|title=Albania's endangered Jewish museum reopens|url=https://news.yahoo.com/albanias-endangered-jewish-museum-reopens-174127642.html|agency=Yahoo news|date=30 September 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Sights ===\n\n[[File:Muzeu Etnografik ne Berat.JPG|thumb|left|230px|The Ethnographic Museum.]]\n\nThe town is still renowned for its historic architecture and scenic beauty and is known as the \"''Town of a Thousand Windows''\", due to the many large windows of the old decorated houses overlooking the town.\n\nIt is unclear whether it really means \"Thousand\" (nj\u00eb mij\u00eb) or \"One over Another\" (nj\u00eb mbi nj\u00eb) windows. Indeed, the quarter is built in a very steep place and windows seem to be one over another. Similar views can be seen in [[Melnik, Bulgaria]], [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]] in Albania,  as well as [[Catanzaro]] in Italy, where an Albanian minority once lived.\n\nThe Citadel overlooks the river and the modern city as well as the old Christian quarter across the river. It is a well preserved area containing narrow streets, Turkish houses and Orthodox churches.\n\n[[File:Berat_-_Kathedrale_1a_Vorhalle.jpg|thumb|right|230px|The [[Onufri Museum of Icons|Onufri Museum]].]]\n\nModern Berat consists of three parts divided by the [[Osum River]]: Gorica (\"little mountain\" in [[Old Church Slavonic]]), Mangalem and Kalaja, the latter being a residential quarter within the old Byzantine citadel that overlooks the town. The town also has a 15th-century mosque and a number of churches of the [[Albanian Orthodox Church]], whose [[autocephaly]] was proclaimed there in 1922. Several of the churches house works by the renowned 16th century painter [[Onufri]].\n\n[[File:BERAT Unesco Albania 2016.jpg|thumb|left|The [[St. Michael's Church (Berat)|St. Michael's Church]] of Berat.]]\n\n[[Berat National Ethnographic Museum]] opened in 1979.<ref name=\"BM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beratmuseum.net/index_etno_en.htm|title=Ethnographic Museum|publisher=Berat Museum|accessdate=5 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405033130/http://beratmuseum.net/index_etno_en.htm|archivedate=5 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It contains a diversity of everyday objects from throughout Berat's history. The museum contains non-movable furniture which hold a number of household objects, wooden case, wall-closets, as well as chimneys and a well. Near the well is an olive press, wool press and many large ceramic dishes, revealing a glimpse of the historical domestic culture of Berat's citizens.<ref name=\"BM\"/> The ground floor has a hall with a model of a medieval street with traditional shops on both sides. On the second floor is an archive, loom, village sitting room, kitchen and sitting room.<ref name=Unesco/><ref name=Museum/><ref name=Canada>{{Cite web |url=https://albca.com/albania/berat.html |title=Berat |accessdate=2010-09-07 |publisher=Albanian Canadian League Information Service |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110233953/http://albca.com/albania/berat.html |archivedate=10 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[Gorica Bridge]], which connects two parts of Berat, was originally built from wood in 1780 and was rebuilt with stone in the 1920s.<ref name=\"Castle\"/> The seven-arch bridge is {{convert|129|m|ft}} long and {{convert|5.3|m|ft}} wide and is built about {{convert|10|m|ft}} above the average water level.<ref name=\"Castle\"/> According to local legend, the original wooden bridge contained a dungeon in which a girl would be incarcerated and starved to appease the spirits responsible for the safety of the bridge.<ref name=Unesco/><ref name=\"Castle\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n[[File:Berat university Albania 2018.2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Albanian University in Berat]].]]\n===Education===\n\n[[Albanian University in Berat]] is a private institution, independent and secular Higher Education, which operates the state fee. Licensed by the Council of Ministers, no. 697 dated 18.06.2009, he opened the doors in the academic year 2009- 2010, offering programs in two faculties: Faculty of Social Sciences Programs in Science Teaching Legal, Political Science and Psychology General Administration and the Faculty of Economics with Learning programs in Banking and Finance-Business Administration. During the first academic year, about 1,000 students attended studies. A year later, this new institution offering undergraduate degrees in study programs: Preschool Teacher Education, Primary Education Teacher, English Language, Nursing, Engineering Computer and Information Technology, thus finalizing the 2010-2011 academic year with the opening of two new faculties: Faculty of Medical Sciences and the Faculty of Architecture and Inxhinierive.Academic Year 2010-2011 finds the University Berat with about 2600 students in the first cycle of study. Since the first year of its inception, the institution pointed at the center of academic life, the promotion of intellectual product and melting learning and research. Through presentations, research and exchange, the University directs and encourages the identification and development of projects that will once again consolidate its primary purpose, scientific development and research toward better quality.\n\n==Climate==\n\nBerat experiences a [[Mediterranean climate]]. Due to its location in a rain shadow of Mount Tomorr the summer in Berat is much warmer than the rest of Mediterranean. \n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Berat (1991 - 2010)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 25\n|Feb record high C = 27\n|Mar record high C = 29\n|Apr record high C = 34\n|May record high C = 38\n|Jun record high C = 43\n|Jul record high C = 44\n|Aug record high C = 43\n|Sep record high C = 42\n|Oct record high C = 35\n|Nov record high C = 30\n|Dec record high C = 28\n|year record high C = 44\n|Jan high C = 14.4\n|Feb high C = 15.3\n|Mar high C = 17.1\n|Apr high C = 22\n|May high C = 25.3\n|Jun high C = 30.4\n|Jul high C = 33.4\n|Aug high C = 33.6\n|Sep high C = 29.2\n|Oct high C = 24\n|Nov high C = 20\n|Dec high C = 15.8\n|Jan low C = 2.0\n|Feb low C = 2.1\n|Mar low C = 4.2\n|Apr low C = 10\n|May low C = 13\n|Jun low C = 17.8\n|Jul low C = 20.3\n|Aug low C = 20.0\n|Sep low C = 17.0\n|Oct low C = 12.5\n|Nov low C = 9.3\n|Dec low C = 3.5\n|Jan record low C = -10\n|Feb record low C = -9\n|Mar record low C = -4\n|Apr record low C = -1\n|May record low C = 3\n|Jun record low C = 8\n|Jul record low C = 14\n|Aug record low C = 12\n|Sep record low C = 6\n|Oct record low C = 0\n|Nov record low C = -3\n|Dec record low C = -8\n|year record low C = -10\n|Jan precipitation mm = 145\n|Feb precipitation mm = 152\n|Mar precipitation mm = 108\n|Apr precipitation mm = 97\n|May precipitation mm = 65\n|Jun precipitation mm = 20\n|Jul precipitation mm = 4\n|Aug precipitation mm = 5\n|Sep precipitation mm = 30\n|Oct precipitation mm = 80\n|Nov precipitation mm = 190\n|Dec precipitation mm = 198\n|source 1 = METEOALB Weather Station\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n==Sports==\nThe [[football (soccer)]] club is [[KS Tomori Berat]].\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Albania}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n|- valign=\"center\" \n|- align=\"center\"\n|\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Lovech]] (Bulgaria)\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[Amasya]] (Turkey)\n||\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[B\u00e9rat]] (France)\n*{{flagicon|Kosovo}} [[Prizren]] (Kosovo)\n||\n*{{flagicon|ISR}} [[Karmiel]] (Israel)\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Politicians===\n*[[Omer Pasha Vrioni II]] \u2013  Albanian ruler from one of the most powerful Albanian families of the 19th century\n*[[Iliaz Vrioni]] \u2013  Albanian politician and land owner. He served as Prime Minister of Albania three times\n*[[Sami Bey Vrioni]] \u2013  Albanian politician, diplomat, and a delegate\n*[[Isuf Vrioni]] \u2013  Albanian translator, diplomat, and Albanian ambassador to UNESCO\n*[[Aziz Vrioni]] \u2013  Ottoman-Albanian politician\n*[[Dhimit\u00ebr Tutulani]] \u2013  Albanian lawyer and politician\n*[[Kas\u00ebm Trebeshina]] \u2013  Albanian partisan, communist prosecutor, actor, and writer\n*[[Sotir Kolea]] \u2013  Albanian folklorist, diplomat and activist of the Albanian National Awakening\n\n===Military===\n*[[Omer Vrioni]] \u2013  Leading Ottoman figure in the Greek War of Independence\n*[[Margarita Tutulani]] \u2013  Anti-fascist and hero of Albania during World War II\n\n===Physicists===\n*[[Af\u00ebrdita Veve\u00e7ka Priftaj]] \u2013  Albanian physicist\n\n===Cinema===\n*[[Kozma Dushi]] \u2013  Albanian recording artist\n\n===Musicians===\n*[[Eni Koci]] \u2013  Albanian female singer\n\n===Religious===\n*[[Christopher of Albania]] \u2013  Primate of the Orthodox Autocephalous Church of Albania from 1937 to 1948\n\n===Sport===\n*[[Myrto Uzuni]] \u2013  Albanian professional footballer who plays as a winger for Croatian club Lokomotiva and the Albania national team\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Codex Beratinus]]\n* [[List of mayors of Berat]]\n* [[Onufri]]\n* [[Osum Canyon]]\n* [[Tomorr Mountain]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Diodorus Siculus]], ''Bibliotheca'' chapters xviii, xix, xx\n* [[Plutarch]], ''[[Parallel Lives]]'', \"[[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius]]\", 18, 31; \"[[Phocion]]\", 31\n* Franca Landucci Gattinoni: L'arte del potere. Vita e opere di Cassandro di Macedonia. Stuttgart 2003. {{ISBN|3-515-08381-2}}\n* ''The Cambridge ancient history'', page 92\n* ''The Regional Directorate of National Culture''\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Berat}}\n{{wikivoyage|Berat}}\n*[http://www.bashkiaberat.gov.al Municipality of Berat]\n*[http://www.muzeumet-berat.al/ Berat Museums]\n*[http://www.goberat.com/ Tourism Information on Berat]\n*[http://gigapan.org/viewGigapan.php?id=32429 1720 megapixel photo of the citdel of Berat]\n*[http://www.journey-stories.com/berat/ Photos of Berat, 2015 year]\n*{{cite news|last1=Byrne|first1=Jane|title=Just Back: Candied walnuts and communism in Albania|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/albania/11782991/Just-Back-Candied-walnuts-and-communism-in-Albania.html|publisher=Telegraph|date=4 Aug 2015}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Berat County}}\n{{Berat Municipality}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in Albania}}\n{{Cultural Monuments in Berat County}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Berat| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Albania]]\n[[Category:Ottoman architecture in Albania| ]]\n[[Category:Antipatrid colonies]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek archaeological sites in Albania]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Municipalities in Berat County]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Berat]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2010-2011 \u2192 2010\u20132011, 1519-1520 \u2192 1519\u20131520", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berat"}
{"title_page": "Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic\n| settlement_type                 = Municipality\n| image_skyline                   = Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic (05).jpg\n| image_shield                    = \n| image_flag                      = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{CZE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[South Bohemian Region|South Bohemian]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[T\u00e1bor District|T\u00e1bor]]\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|49|19|38|N|14|35|53|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map                     = Czech Republic\n| area_total_km2                  = 7.01\n| population_total                = 126\n| population_as_of                = 2006\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| elevation_m                     = 475\n| postal_code_type                = Postal&nbsp;code\n| postal_code                     = 391&nbsp;75\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[T\u00e1bor District]] in the [[South Bohemian Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|7.01|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 126 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nSkr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic lies approximately {{convert|11|km|mi|0}} south-west of [[T\u00e1bor]], {{convert|41|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} north of [[\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]], and {{convert|86|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Prague]].\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic (001).jpg|Village chapel (right) and old fire department store (left)\nFile:Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic (004).jpg|Gardens\nFile:Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic (07).jpg|Houses\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090531124130/http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0317/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of T\u00e1bor District]\n\n{{T\u00e1bor District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skrychov U Malsic}}\n[[Category:Villages in T\u00e1bor District]]\n\n\n{{SouthBohemia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic\n| settlement_type                 = Municipality\n| image_skyline                   = Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic (05).jpg\n| image_shield                    = \n| image_flag                      = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{CZE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[South Bohemian Region|South Bohemian]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[T\u00e1bor District|T\u00e1bor]]\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|49|19|38|N|14|35|53|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map                     = Czech Republic\n| area_total_km2                  = 7.01\n| population_total                = 126\n| population_as_of                = 2006\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| elevation_m                     = 475\n| postal_code_type                = Postal&nbsp;code\n| postal_code                     = 391&nbsp;75\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Skr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[T\u00e1bor District]] in the [[South Bohemian Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\n{{Commonscat}}\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|7.01|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 126 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nSkr\u00fdchov u Mal\u0161ic lies approximately {{convert|11|km|mi|0}} south-west of [[T\u0